    <title>Combined summary - A critique of bitcoin open source community</title>
    <updated>2023-06-07T17:49:51.246454+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2013-October/003362.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Bitcoin development has faced challenges related to communication, transparency, and support for newcomers in the community. In one instance, Wladimir van der Laan expressed frustration with unhelpful behavior from some Bitcoin developers on forums. While Jean-Paul Kogelman suggested creating an area for proposals like NODE_BLOOM and BIP 38, Peter Todd proposed subdirectories within the repository that map onto the status of the BIP.The importance of clear communication and transparency was highlighted in a Berkeley School of Information article shared by Nathan Merrill, prompting further discussion about the need for better communication and support for newcomers. Jeff Garzik proposed that Bitcoin Improvement Proposals (BIPs) be done as a GitHub repository to increase transparency, which was supported by Peter Todd. In 2013, a proposal was made to change the BIP process to include subdirectories based on the status of the BIP, and the use of IETF was also suggested. Additionally, Mitar shared an article about adopting a code of conduct similar to Ubuntu's, emphasizing collaboration, respect, and diversity. The process for obtaining a BIP number was discussed by Jean-Paul Kogelman and Luke Dashjr. The BIP process is an agile one that balances necessary features and documentation, helping maintain the momentum of Bitcoin in the short to medium term. Other systems like Python, XMPP, and BitTorrent also use similar enhancement proposal processes. The conversion of BIPs to GitHub was completed in 2013, directly copying from the bitcoin.it wiki using MediaWiki support. Despite proposals for changes to the BIP process, limited response has been received on the mailing list. One contributor suggested discussing them further on the mailing list after posting their technical review on Bitcointalk. Posting reviews on the mailing list is recommended since it is the initial platform for proposals to be submitted and discussed before being implemented.While criticism regarding the gender skew in open-source development has been raised, it is not the appropriate platform to discuss it in detail.</summary>
